title: Respect
description: After spending months at the Betty Ford Center, TV reporter Murphy Brown tries to re-enter her life. The task is complicated by the addition to her show of a former Miss America as co-reporter, and a new Executive Producer who's half her age.

title: Devil with a Blue Dress On
description: Murphy's animosity towards Corky grows when she's forced to take her on to help with an important story.

title: Nowhere to Run
description: Miles becomes the target of death threats when the show investigates the dealings of a mob boss.

title: Signed, Sealed, Delivered
description: Murphy struggles to maintain her professionalism when her next interview is a man she was married to twenty years before.

title: Murphy's Pony
description: Shortly before Christmas three children show up at FYI with a note from their mother. She says she cannot take care of them anymore and thinks Murphy would make a good mother.

title: Baby Love
description: A friend of Murphy's is having a baby and Murphy starts to wonder if something is missing in her life.

title: Set Me Free
description: Murphy's having a rotten day, complicated by a gunman who interrupts the show and demands they read his statement on the air and it gets capped off by the painter she hired to do her kitchen sticking around to finish "extending myself." During this whole ordeal, she is craving cigarettes and a drink, and definitely a soft number 2 pencil.

title: And So He Goes
description: The man that Murphy has been in a prank war for decades with dies suddenly, and asks that she eulogize him.

title: I Would Have Danced All Night
description: Murphy can't understand why she isn't invited to the Inaugural Ball, and can't get anyone to take her.

title: Kyle
description: Murphy's story gets an innocent inmate released. Everyone feels sorry for him, so they give him a job as Murphy's secretary.

title: Off the Job Experience
description: When Murphy humiliates on air an US army militant- Miles takes the decision to suspend her from work.

title: Why Do Fools Fall in Love?
description: Frank & Murphy fix each others blind dates, while Miles has to deal with his break up with Jackie and Jim wonders what to do with an attractive lady that wants him. We learn more than what we would have wanted to for Phil's marriage life.

title: Soul Man
description: Murphy get furious when she is denied an access into the last gentlemen's only club in Washington. That makes her relationship with Jim uptight and stirs a war between the sexes into the office.

title: It's How You Play the Game
description: When the FYI show goes lower onto the ratings - the network suggests to it's journalists to make the news more pleasant and easy to the public. Though the FYI team wouldn't like to be less professional - they struggle with the reality of having to face a tough decision and compromise for the sakes of Frank's touching story for the homeless being seen by a larger sum of people.

title: Mama Said
description: Murphy's mom whom she was never close to comes for a visit. And she spends all the time fawning after Murphy which has Murphy perplexed.

title: Moscow on the Potomac
description: The FYI show accepts a guest from the USSR - the newswoman Vladia.

title: My Dinner with Einstein
description: Murphy is excited to meet "the nowadays's Einstein" Victor Rudman. She tries to challenge herself on a date with him, since "You can't judge a book by it's cover", but discovers that geniuses can also be unpleasant people.

title: Funnies Girl
description: Murphy tries to deliver a joke, but her insulting comment is aired on Tv. She is faced with the consequences the next day as a cartoonist, named Pat O'Shea started a column in the newspaper, named "The adventures of Mouthy Brown".

title: The Brothers Silverberg
description: Miles' brother comes to town and romances Murphy to Miles' chagrin.

Underdogs
description: When the gang gets the TV Q's and they see how low Miller's is, they think that he's on his way out but Kay says that as long as Miller is on Lansing's good side he's not going anywhere. When Miller sees his numbers, he asks Murphy if he should play hardball with Lansing when he renegotiates his contracts. At first Murphy was about to tell him that's absurd but she then tells him that he should and makes up a thing called the Underdog theory which she says that since he's at the bottom, he can only go up. So he and his agent go to Lansing and ask for a raise and they get kicked out. That's when Murphy tells them to make a ruckus, which gets Miller fired. When the gang learns what Murphy did they go to Miller to tell him that the Underdog theory is bogus. So they go to his place and they find him partying like crazy. He thinks that it's only a matter of time before he gets a new offer. When they tell him, he goes into shock cause he just spent all of his money. Murphy offers to find him a job but no luck. Later his agent shows up with offers from other networks. That's when Lansing shows up and offers to give him a big raise. Murphy is shocked that Lansing is doing this. He says he has to cause Miller is hot property. Later Frank goes to Lansing asking for a raise and throws things around and Lansing belts him.

title: And That's the Way It Was?
A Butcher, a Faker, a Bummed-Out Promo Maker
